  "target_response": {
    "text": "Neither extreme — take an active recovery day. Screaming quads after your first spin class in months is textbook delayed-onset soreness from unaccustomed work, and a momentary head rush when you stood up quickly is a normal blood-pressure adjustment that settles in seconds; near-fainting during activity, or dizziness that lingers, would be the different case that warrants a doctor. You logged about 7.4 hours of sleep, which helps the repair along. I don't have recovery or heart-rate data for you, so go by feel: an easy walk or gentle cycle plus some light stretching will ease the stairs faster than full rest, and the soreness should fade noticeably over the next couple of days. Book your next spin class after that — the second one always hurts far less.",
